{"parse":{"title":"Political Economy of Research and Innovation","pageid":55807611,"revid":826605694,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Political Economy of Research and Innovation</b> (PERI) (or sometimes political economy of <a href=\"/wiki/Technoscience\" title=\"Technoscience\">technoscience</a>) is an emerging academic field at the interface of <a href=\"/wiki/Science_and_Technology_Studies\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Science and Technology Studies\">science and technology studies</a> and political economy. It focuses on the production, distribution, and consumption of <a href=\"/wiki/Knowledge\" title=\"Knowledge\">knowledge</a>, and how these shape and are shaped by different political economies.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Most scholars in this field have so-far focused on the two-way relationship between science, technology, and innovation and political economic processes, practices, and logics. \n</p><p>It has its origins in the critique of neoclassical or orthodox <a href=\"/wiki/Economics_of_science\" title=\"Economics of science\">economics of science</a> by scholars like <a href=\"/wiki/Philip_Mirowski\" title=\"Philip Mirowski\">Philip Mirowski</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> the 'economic turn' in science and technology studies (see <a href=\"/wiki/Social_studies_of_finance\" title=\"Social studies of finance\">social studies of finance</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Sociology_of_valuation\" title=\"Sociology of valuation\">valuation studies</a>),<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Innovation_studies&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Innovation studies (page does not exist)\">innovation studies</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Science_policy\" title=\"Science policy\">science policy</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Examples of the field include:\n</p>\n<ul><li>An annual <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://politicaleconomyoftechnoscience.wordpress.com/\">Changing Political Economy of Research and Innovation</a> (CPERI) workshop which has been held in Lancaster (UK 2012), Toronto (Canada 2013), San Diego (USA 2015), Liege (Belgium 2016), and Boston (USA 2017). The workshop will be held in Lancaster (UK) again this year.</li>\n<li>Programmatic handbooks like <i>The</i> <i>Routledge Handbook of the Political Economy of Science</i> (2017, edited by David Tyfield, Rebecca Lave, Samuel Randalls, and Charles Thorpe)<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and <i>Critical Studies of Innovation</i> (2017, edited by Beno\u00eet Godin and Dominique Vinck) published by Edward Elgar.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Special issues of academic journals.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Graduate courses in science and technology studies programs.<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://sts.gradstudies.yorku.ca/files/2014/10/STS6312-W15.pdf\">[1]</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://campus.tum.de/tumonline/wbLv.wbShowLVDetail?pStpSpNr=950348612\">[1]</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Political_Economy_of_Research_and_Innovation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></spa